Q: how do i get specific values from specific keys in dictionary? A: <p>The only idea I can think of is that you are not getting the keys from the dictionary correctly. You can do it like this:</p>
<pre><code>for dic in forms:

      // I get the keys from the current dictionary
    keys = dic.keys()
    for key in keys:
        if key.startswith( &quot;7&quot; ):
            print( key )
</code></pre>

Q: How do I optimize my 2D Array Point Searcher A: <p>Just to add some info about the generated code - at first glance there are 2 major problems with the code generated by the AI (besides reinventing the wheel):</p>
<ol>
<li><p>The sample array is not sorted so the binary search will not work (and you need to sort it which can be not an easy task for multidimensional array).</p>
</li>
<li><p>The array allocations in the <code>while</code> loop:</p>
<pre class="lang-cs prettyprint-override"><code>int[] point1 = {arr[mid, 0],arr[mid, 1]};
</code></pre>
<p>which also can easily be fixed by moving the array creation outside of the loop:</p>
<pre class="lang-cs prettyprint-override"><code>int[] point1 = new int[2];
while (high &gt;= low)
{
    // ...
    // I use here the &quot;value tuple assign trick&quot;
    // but you can manually perform the actions 
    (point1[0], point1[1]) = (arr[mid, 0], arr[mid, 1]); 
    // ...
}
</code></pre>
</li>
</ol>
<p>Other than that I strongly agree with point made by <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/users/14868997/charlieface">Charlieface</a> - the best option here would be to switch from multidimensional arrays completely and use a designated type to represent your data (i.e. some kind of <code>Point</code>, which usually should be a <code>struct</code> in this context), which will improve the maintainability and readability of the code greatly (with potentially possible positive performance benefits).</p>

Q: SetValues Formik Function disables Formik HandleSubmit A: <p>Turns out the issue was the is Validating Flag being set to true when you call setFieldValue so the simplest solution is to pass a third argument to setFieldValue to manually turn off validation:</p>

<pre><code>  submit = () =&gt; {
    this.props.setFieldValue('submit', true, false)
    this.props.handleSubmit()
  }
</code></pre>
